1️⃣ Stack – Push / Pop (LIFO)
🔹 Concept

Stack follows LIFO → Last In, First Out.

🧠 Python Code (4 lines)
s=[]
s.append(10); s.append(20)
print(s.pop())
print(s)

🖥️ Output
20
[10]

📖 Explanation

append() → Push operation

pop() → Remove last element

20 was inserted last → removed first

⏱️ Interview Insight

Time Complexity: O(1) for push & pop

Used in:

Function calls

Undo/Redo

Expression evaluation

🎤 Interview Explanation

“Stack uses LIFO principle where insertion and deletion happen from the same end.”

2️⃣ Valid Parentheses (Very Important Interview Problem)
🔹 Problem

Check if brackets are balanced: "()[]{}"

🧠 Python Code (6 lines)
s="()[]{}"; st=[]
for c in s:
    if c in "([{": st.append(c)
    elif not st or "([{".index(st.pop())!=")]}".index(c):
        print(False); break
else: print(True)

🖥️ Output
True

📖 Explanation

Push opening brackets onto stack.

When closing bracket appears:

Check if it matches last opening.

If mismatch → False.

If stack empty at end → True.

⏱️ Interview Insight

Time Complexity: O(n)

Space Complexity: O(n)

🎤 Interview Explanation

“I use a stack to match opening and closing brackets in order.”

🎤 FAANG Interview Round (Professional Answers)

Q1. What principle does stack follow?
A: LIFO – Last In, First Out.

Q2. Where are stacks used in real systems?
A: Function calls, recursion stack, undo features.

Q3. Why is stack perfect for parentheses problems?
A: Because matching must happen in reverse order.

Q4. What happens if stack is empty and closing bracket appears?
A: The string is invalid.

